\section{Related Work}

\paragraph{Training-Based Concept Erasure.}
A prominent line of work modifies diffusion model parameters to permanently remove unsafe concepts. Erased Stable Diffusion (ESD)~\citep{gandikota2023erasing} fine-tunes the cross-attention layers to minimize the probability of generating target concepts. Self-Distillation Decoding (SDD)~\citep{kim2023towards} employs self-distillation to guide model weights toward a safer distribution. Unified Concept Editing (UCE)~\citep{gandikota2024unified} introduces closed-form weight updates that eliminate the need for iterative training, while RECE~\citep{gong2024reliable} improves reliability through eraser ensembles. Concept Ablation~\citep{kumari2023ablating} and Forget-Me-Not~\citep{zhang2024forget} explore alternative fine-tuning strategies. While these methods achieve strong suppression for specific concepts, they share fundamental limitations: each concept requires separate training, parameter modification risks catastrophic forgetting, and the altered model remains constrained even for entirely benign prompts.

\paragraph{Training-Free Inference-Time Guidance.}
An alternative paradigm preserves model parameters and intervenes only during inference. Safe Latent Diffusion (SLD)~\citep{schramowski2023safe} manipulates classifier-free guidance (CFG) to steer denoising trajectories away from harmful concepts, providing four strength levels (Weak, Medium, Strong, Max). SEGA~\citep{brack2023sega} extends this with semantic guidance directions. More recently, SAFREE~\citep{yoon2024safree} operates jointly in text and latent spaces, projecting harmful tokens orthogonal to the toxic subspace. However, these methods apply suppression globally across all spatial locations, inevitably causing semantic drift and quality degradation for benign prompts. Our prior work, ASCG~\citep{gil2026ascg}, introduced spatial selectivity via Grad-CAM localization but relied on auxiliary classifiers and lacked multi-concept support. \ours{} fundamentally extends this line by replacing classifier-dependent detection with example-based CLIP embeddings, introducing a dual-probe spatial mechanism, and enabling simultaneous multi-concept erasure.

\paragraph{Concept Detection in Diffusion Models.}
Detecting when and where unsafe concepts emerge during generation is crucial for selective intervention. Classifier-based approaches~\citep{Dhariwal2021Diffusion} use external models to monitor the denoising trajectory, but require concept-specific classifiers. Prompt-based filtering~\citep{rando2022red} checks input text for unsafe keywords, but is easily circumvented by adversarial rephrasing. Recent work on representation engineering~\citep{zou2023representation} suggests that concept directions in latent space can be identified from small example sets. Our CAS mechanism builds on this insight, using the cosine alignment between denoising directions and exemplar-defined concept vectors to gate intervention without any external classifier.

\paragraph{Safety Evaluation for T2I Models.}
Evaluating the safety of generated images remains challenging. NudeNet~\citep{notai_nudenet_2019} provides automated nudity detection but lacks semantic understanding. The I2P benchmark~\citep{schramowski2023safe} introduces a comprehensive prompt set across safety categories but relies on simple classifiers for evaluation. MJ-Bench~\citep{chen2024mjbench} establishes a standardized protocol for evaluating multimodal judges on safety preference tasks. Recent vision-language models (VLMs) such as Qwen-VL~\citep{bai2025qwen3vl} and LLaVA~\citep{liu2023visual} offer more nuanced safety assessments through free-form analysis. We adopt a VLM-based evaluation framework using Qwen3-VL and validate its reliability through MJ-Bench benchmarking and cross-validator agreement analysis.
